        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_02_04_page02.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>Edgeworth's Town<lb/>
                        <date when="1816-02-04"/>February 04, 1816<lb/></dateline>
                </opener>
                <p> <note place="top">1 1/2 Muslin<lb/>
                    6 Footing<lb/>
                    1/3 - 4<lb/>
                    Shoe strings<lb/>
                    <unclear>Curls</unclear> - H -Pins<lb/>
                    <unclear>Barnard</unclear></note><lb/></p>
                <p> My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName> I am<lb/>
                    afraid you will be <choice><orig>appre-<lb/>
                        hensive</orig><reg>apprehensive</reg></choice> of trouble the moment<lb/>
                    you see my handwriting<lb/>
                    - and what is worse you<lb/>
                    will not be mistaken.<lb/></p>
                <p>  Will you let trouble you to<lb/>
                    buy for me what I cannot<lb/>
                    get in this country a little<lb/>
                    real India muslin - Jaconette<lb/>
                    or of that degree of <hi rend="underline">thickness</hi> -<lb/>
                    not <hi rend="underline">book muslin</hi> as it is for<lb/>
                    flounce &amp; trimming the<lb/>
                    neck of a morning gown - <lb/></p>
                <p> I wish it to be very fine &amp; am<lb/>
                    aware that it must be dear<lb/>
                    I want only a yard or yard<lb/>
                    &amp; half - the width not <choice><orig>ma<lb/>
                        terial</orig><reg>material</reg></choice>- If a remnant of a little<lb/>
                    more than that quantity fell<lb/>
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_02_04_page03.jpg"/>             
                    in your way I would take it<lb/></p>
                <p> - I am in no hurry so use<lb/>
                    your own time &amp; opportunity<lb/>
                    - Whenever you meet with<lb/>
                    it send it between the leaves<lb/>
                    of any pamphlet <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Miles</persName><lb/>
                    would recommend - Or if<lb/>
                    all London should not afford<lb/>
                    one pamphlet worth <del></del><lb/>
                    reading put the muslin<lb/>
                    between the outside pasteboard<lb/>
                    covers of any old book &amp; direct<lb/>
                    the same to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E.</persName><placeName>Edgeworths Town</placeName><lb/>
                    under cover to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC1">CJ. J Fox Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi></persName>.<lb/>
                    under a third outside cover<lb/>
                    to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaylW1">W. Taylor Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi></persName> <placeName>Castle Dublin</placeName><lb/></p>
                <p> In the same packet be<lb/>
                    so kind to send me 6 yards of<lb/>
                    footing for joining lace together<lb/></p>
                <p> Pray tell me whether <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi><lb/>
                    Hunter</persName> paid you my dear <choice><orig>Ma-<lb/>
                        <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_02_04_page04.jpg"/><lb/>             
                        dam</orig><reg>Madam</reg></choice> last March or April<lb/>
                    for the broad lace you were<lb/>
                    so kind to purchase for me<lb/>
                    - I hope to goodness he did &amp;<lb/>
                    that I am not so shabby as<lb/>
                    to have trespassed on you<lb/>
                    all this time or so negligent<lb/>
                    as not to know it.<lb/></p>
                <p> My father is rather better<lb/>
                    than he has been for some time<lb/>
                    But his health is far from<lb/>
                    being reestablished &amp; we are<lb/>
                    with reason very anxious<lb/>
                    about him -<lb/></p>
                <p>I hope you have found <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Mile2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                    Miles's</persName> health improved<lb/>
                by his quitting business <unclear>page torn</unclear><lb/>
                least somebody should <unclear>page torn</unclear><lb/>
                    better for <hi rend="underline">that</hi> which we <choice><orig>selfish<lb/>
                        ly</orig><reg>selfishly</reg></choice> can never cease to regret<lb/></p>
             <closer> 
                 Believe me very truly<lb/>
                 your <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                </closer>
                <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
                <closer><!--Use the <closer> element again to hold Address Leaf information.-->
                    <address>
                        <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_02_04_page01.jpg"/>
                        <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName><addrLine/>
                        <persName xml:id="ChatX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Chaters</persName><addrLine/>
                        <placeName>Corn Hill</placeName><addrLine/>
                    </address>
                </closer>
            </div>
